# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: quicksort-algorithm
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] A **comparison sort** is a type of sorting algorithm that only reads the list elements through a single abstract comparison operation (often a "less than or equal to" operator or a three-way comparison) that determines which of two elements should occur first in the final sorted list.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] It is possible that both *a* ≤ *b* and *b* ≤ *a* with *a* ≠ *b*; in this case either may come first in the sorted list.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] In a stable sort, the input order determines the sorted order in this case.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Comparison sorts studied in the literature are "comparison-based".
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Elements *a* and *b* can be swapped or otherwise re-arranged by the algorithm only when the order between these elements has been established based on the outcomes of prior comparisons.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] This is the case when the order between *a* and *b* can be derived via the transitive closure of these prior comparison outcomes.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] For comparison-based sorts, the decision to execute basic operations other than comparisons is based on the outcome of comparisons.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Hence in a time analysis, the number of executed comparisons is used to determine upper bound estimates for the number of executed basic operations such as swaps or assignments.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] A metaphor for thinking about comparison sorts is that someone has a set of unlabelled weights and a balance scale.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Their goal is to line up the weights in order by their weight without any information except that obtained by placing two weights on the scale and seeing which one is heavier (or if they weigh the same).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] There are fundamental limits on the performance of comparison sorts.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] A comparison sort must have an average-case lower bound of Ω(*n* log *n*) comparison operations, which is known as linearithmic time.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] This is a consequence of the limited information available through comparisons alone — or, to put it differently, of the vague algebraic structure of totally ordered sets.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] In this sense, mergesort, heapsort, and introsort are asymptotically optimal in terms of the number of comparisons they must perform, although this metric neglects other operations.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Non-comparison sorts (such as the examples discussed below) can achieve O(*n*) performance by using operations other than comparisons, allowing them to sidestep this lower bound (assuming elements are constant-sized).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Comparison sorts may run faster on some lists; many adaptive sorts such as insertion sort run in O(*n*) time on an already-sorted or nearly-sorted list.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The Ω(*n* log *n*) lower bound applies only to the case in which the input list can be in any possible order.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Despite these limitations, comparison sorts offer the notable practical advantage that control over the comparison function allows sorting of many different datatypes and fine control over how the list is sorted.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Comparison sorts generally adapt more easily to complex orders such as the order of floating-point numbers.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Additionally, once a comparison function is written, any comparison sort can be used without modification; non-comparison sorts typically require specialized versions for each datatype.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] This flexibility, together with the efficiency of the above comparison sorting algorithms on modern computers, has led to widespread preference for comparison sorts in most practical work.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Some sorting problems admit a strictly faster solution than the Ω(*n* log *n*) bound for comparison sorting by using non-comparison sorts; an example is integer sorting, where all keys are integers.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] When the keys form a small (compared to n) range, counting sort is an example algorithm that runs in linear time.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Other integer sorting algorithms, such as radix sort, are not asymptotically faster than comparison sorting, but can be faster in practice.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The problem of sorting pairs of numbers by their sum is not subject to the Ω(*n*² log *n*) bound either (the square resulting from the pairing up); the best known algorithm still takes O(*n*² log *n*) time, but only O(*n*²) comparisons.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The number of comparisons that a comparison sort algorithm requires increases in proportion to $n\log(n)$ , where n is the number of elements to sort.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Given a list of distinct numbers (we can assume this because this is a worst-case analysis), there are n factorial permutations exactly one of which is the list in sorted order.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The sort algorithm must gain enough information from the comparisons to identify the correct permutation.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] If the algorithm always completes after at most $f(n)$ steps, it cannot distinguish more than $2^{f(n)}$ cases because the keys are distinct and each comparison has only two possible outcomes.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] This provides the lower-bound part of the claim.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] A more precise bound can be given via Stirling's approximation.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] An upper bound of the same form, with the same leading term as the bound obtained from Stirling's approximation, follows from the existence of the algorithms that attain this bound in the worst case, like merge sort.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The above argument provides an *absolute*, rather than only asymptotic lower bound on the number of comparisons, namely $\left\lceil \log _{2}(n!)\right\rceil$ comparisons.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] This lower bound is fairly good (it can be approached within a linear tolerance by a simple merge sort), but it is known to be inexact.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] For example, $\left\lceil \log _{2}(13!)\right\rceil =33$ , but the minimal number of comparisons to sort 13 elements has been proved to be 34.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Determining the *exact* number of comparisons needed to sort a given number of entries is a computationally hard problem even for small *n*, and no simple formula for the solution is known.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] For some of the few concrete values that have been computed, see OEIS: A036604.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] A similar bound applies to the average number of comparisons.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] it is impossible to determine which order the input is in with fewer than log2(*n*!) comparisons on average.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] This can be most easily seen using concepts from information theory.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The Shannon entropy of such a random permutation is log2(*n*!) bits.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Since a comparison can give only two results, the maximum amount of information it provides is 1 bit.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Therefore, after *k* comparisons the remaining entropy of the permutation, given the results of those comparisons, is at least log2(*n*!) − *k* bits on average.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] To perform the sort, complete information is needed, so the remaining entropy must be 0.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] It follows that *k* must be at least log2(*n*!) on average.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The lower bound derived via information theory is phrased as 'information-theoretic lower bound'.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The information-theoretic lower bound is correct, but may be far from the strongest possible lower bound.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] For example, the information-theoretic lower bound of selection is $\left\lceil \log _{2}(n)\right\rceil$ whereas $n-1$ comparisons are needed by an adversarial argument.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The interplay between information-theoretic lower bound and the true lower bound are much like a real-valued function lower-bounding an integer function.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] However, this is not exactly correct when the average case is considered.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] To unearth what happens while analyzing the average case, the key is that what does 'average' refer to?
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] With some knowledge of information theory, the information-theoretic lower bound averages over the set of all permutations as a whole.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] But any computer algorithms (under what are believed currently) must treat each permutation as an individual instance of the problem.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Hence, the average lower bound we're searching for is averaged over all individual cases.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] To search for the lower bound relating to the non-achievability of computers, we adopt the Decision tree model.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Let's rephrase a bit of what our objective is.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] In the Decision tree model, the lower bound to be shown is the lower bound of the average length of root-to-leaf paths of an $n!$ -leaf binary tree (in which each leaf corresponds to a permutation).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The minimum average length of a binary tree with a given number of leaves is achieved by a balanced full binary tree, because any other binary tree can have its path length reduced by moving a pair of leaves to a higher position.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] For example, for *n* = 3, the information-theoretic lower bound for the average case is approximately 2.58, while the average lower bound derived via Decision tree model is 8/3, approximately 2.67.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] In the case that multiple items may have the same key, there is no obvious statistical interpretation for the term "average case", so an argument like the above cannot be applied without making specific assumptions about the distribution of keys.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Can easy compute for real algorithm sorted-list-merging (array are sorted n-blocks with size 1, merge to 1–1 to 2, merge 2–2 to 4...).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] If a list is already close to sorted, according to some measure of sortedness, the number of comparisons required to sort it can be smaller.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] An adaptive sort takes advantage of this "presortedness" and runs more quickly on nearly-sorted inputs, often while still maintaining an $O(n\log n)$ worst case time bound.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] An example is adaptive heap sort, a sorting algorithm based on Cartesian trees.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/comparison-sort] It takes time $O(n\log k)$ , where k is the average, over all values x in the sequence, of the number of times the sequence jumps from below x to above x or vice versa.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In computer science, **divide and conquer** is an algorithm design paradigm.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] A divide-and-conquer algorithm recursively breaks down a problem into two or more sub-problems of the same or related type, until these become simple enough to be solved directly.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The solutions to the sub-problems are then combined to give a solution to the original problem.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Designing efficient divide-and-conquer algorithms can be difficult.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] As in mathematical induction, it is often necessary to generalize the problem to make it amenable to a recursive solution.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The correctness of a divide-and-conquer algorithm is usually proved by mathematical induction, and its computational cost is often determined by solving recurrence relations.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The divide-and-conquer paradigm is often used to find an optimal solution of a problem.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Its basic idea is to decompose a given problem into two or more similar, but simpler, subproblems, to solve them in turn, and to compose their solutions to solve the given problem.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Problems of sufficient simplicity are solved directly.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, to sort a given list of *n* natural numbers, split it into two lists of about *n*/2 numbers each, sort each of them in turn, and interleave both results appropriately to obtain the sorted version of the given list (see the picture).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This approach is known as the merge sort algorithm.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The name "divide and conquer" is sometimes applied to algorithms that reduce each problem to only one sub-problem, such as the binary search algorithm for finding a record in a sorted list (or its analogue in numerical computing, the bisection algorithm for root finding).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] These algorithms can be implemented more efficiently than general divide-and-conquer algorithms; in particular, if they use tail recursion, they can be converted into simple loops.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Under this broad definition, however, every algorithm that uses recursion or loops could be regarded as a "divide-and-conquer algorithm".
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Therefore, some authors consider that the name "divide and conquer" should be used only when each problem may generate two or more subproblems.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The name **decrease and conquer** has been proposed instead for the single-subproblem class.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Early examples of these algorithms are primarily decrease and conquer – the original problem is successively broken down into *single* subproblems, and indeed can be solved iteratively.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Binary search, a decrease-and-conquer algorithm where the subproblems are of roughly half the original size, has a long history.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] While a clear description of the algorithm on computers appeared in 1946 in an article by John Mauchly, the idea of using a sorted list of items to facilitate searching dates back at least as far as Babylonia in 200 BC.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Another ancient decrease-and-conquer algorithm is the Euclidean algorithm to compute the greatest common divisor of two numbers by reducing the numbers to smaller and smaller equivalent subproblems, which dates to several centuries BC.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] An early two-subproblem D&C algorithm that was specifically developed for computers and properly analyzed is the merge sort algorithm, invented by John von Neumann in 1945.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Another notable example is the algorithm invented by Anatolii A.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Karatsuba in 1960 that could multiply two *n*-digit numbers in $O(n^{\log _{2}3})$ operations (in Big O notation).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This algorithm disproved Andrey Kolmogorov's 1956 conjecture that $\Omega (n^{2})$ operations would be required for that task.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This is related to a radix sort, described for punch-card sorting machines as early as 1929.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Divide and conquer is a powerful tool for solving conceptually difficult problems: all it requires is a way of breaking the problem into sub-problems, of solving the trivial cases, and of combining sub-problems to the original problem.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Similarly, decrease and conquer only requires reducing the problem to a single smaller problem, such as the classic Tower of Hanoi puzzle, which reduces moving a tower of height n to move a tower of height $n-1$ .
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The divide-and-conquer paradigm often helps in the discovery of efficient algorithms.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] It was the key, for example, to Karatsuba's fast multiplication method, the quicksort and mergesort algorithms, the Strassen algorithm for matrix multiplication, and fast Fourier transforms.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In all these examples, the D&C approach led to an improvement in the asymptotic cost of the solution.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For other types of divide-and-conquer approaches, running times can also be generalized.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] If, instead, the work of splitting the problem and combining the partial solutions take $cn^{2}$ time, and there are 2 subproblems where each has size ${\frac {n}{2}}$ , then the running time of the divide-and-conquer algorithm is bounded by $O(n^{2})$ .
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Divide-and-conquer algorithms are naturally adapted for execution in multi-processor machines, especially shared-memory systems where the communication of data between processors does not need to be planned in advance because distinct sub-problems can be executed on different processors.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Divide-and-conquer algorithms naturally tend to make efficient use of memory caches.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The reason is that once a sub-problem is small enough, it and all its sub-problems can, in principle, be solved within the cache, without accessing the slower main memory.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] An algorithm designed to exploit the cache in this way is called *cache-oblivious*, because it does not contain the cache size as an explicit parameter.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Moreover, D&C algorithms can be designed for important algorithms (e.g., sorting, FFTs, and matrix multiplication) to be *optimal* cache-oblivious algorithms–they use the cache in a probably optimal way, in an asymptotic sense, regardless of the cache size.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The same advantage exists with regards to other hierarchical storage systems, such as NUMA or virtual memory, as well as for multiple levels of cache: once a sub-problem is small enough, it can be solved within a given level of the hierarchy, without accessing the higher (slower) levels.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In computations with rounded arithmetic, e.g. with floating-point numbers, a divide-and-conquer algorithm may yield more accurate results than a superficially equivalent iterative method.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, one can add *N* numbers either by a simple loop that adds each datum to a single variable, or by a D&C algorithm called pairwise summation that breaks the data set into two halves, recursively computes the sum of each half, and then adds the two sums.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] While the second method performs the same number of additions as the first and pays the overhead of the recursive calls, it is usually more accurate.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Divide-and-conquer algorithms are naturally implemented as recursive procedures.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In that case, the partial sub-problems leading to the one currently being solved are automatically stored in the procedure call stack.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] A recursive function is a function that calls itself within its definition.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Divide-and-conquer algorithms can also be implemented by a non-recursive program that stores the partial sub-problems in some explicit data structure, such as a stack, queue, or priority queue.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This approach allows more freedom in the choice of the sub-problem that is to be solved next, a feature that is important in some applications — e.g. in breadth-first recursion and the branch-and-bound method for function optimization.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This approach is also the standard solution in programming languages that do not provide support for recursive procedures.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In recursive implementations of D&C algorithms, one must make sure that there is sufficient memory allocated for the recursion stack, otherwise, the execution may fail because of stack overflow.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] D&C algorithms that are time-efficient often have relatively small recursion depth.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, the quicksort algorithm can be implemented so that it never requires more than $\log _{2}n$ nested recursive calls to sort n items.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Stack overflow can be difficult to prevent when using recursive procedures, since many compilers treat the recursion stack as a contiguous block of memory, and some reserve a fixed amount of space for it.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In addition, compilers may store more information on the recursion stack than is strictly required, including the return address, unchanged parameters, and the procedure’s local variables.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] As a result, the likelihood of stack overflow may be reduced by limiting the number of parameters and local variables in the recursive procedure, or by replacing recursion with an explicit stack data structure.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In any recursive algorithm, there is considerable freedom in the choice of the *base cases*, the small subproblems that are solved directly in order to terminate the recursion.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Choosing the smallest or simplest possible base cases is more elegant and usually leads to simpler programs, because there are fewer cases to consider and they are easier to solve.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, a Fast Fourier Transform algorithm could stop the recursion when the input is a single sample, and the quicksort list-sorting algorithm could stop when the input is the empty list; in both examples, there is only one base case to consider, and it requires no processing.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] On the other hand, efficiency often improves if the recursion is stopped at relatively large base cases, and these are solved non-recursively, resulting in a hybrid algorithm.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This strategy avoids the overhead of recursive calls that do little or no work and may also allow the use of specialized non-recursive algorithms that, for those base cases, are more efficient than explicit recursion.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] A general procedure for a simple hybrid recursive algorithm is *short-circuiting the base case*, also known as *arm's-length recursion*.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In this case, whether the next step will result in the base case is checked before the function call, avoiding an unnecessary function call.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, in a tree, rather than recursing to a child node and then checking whether it is null, checking null before recursing avoids half the function calls in some algorithms on binary trees.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Since a D&C algorithm eventually reduces each problem or sub-problem instance to a large number of base instances, these often dominate the overall cost of the algorithm, especially when the splitting/joining overhead is low.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Note that these considerations do not depend on whether recursion is implemented by the compiler or by an explicit stack.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Thus, for example, many library implementations of quicksort will switch to a simple loop-based insertion sort (or similar) algorithm once the number of items to be sorted is sufficiently small.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Note that, if the empty list were the only base case, sorting a list with n entries would entail maximally n quicksort calls that would do nothing but return immediately.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Increasing the base cases to lists of size 2 or less will eliminate most of those do-nothing calls, and more generally a base case larger than 2 is typically used to reduce the fraction of time spent in function-call overhead or stack manipulation.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, this approach is used in some efficient FFT implementations, where the base cases are unrolled implementations of divide-and-conquer FFT algorithms for a set of fixed sizes.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Source-code generation methods may be used to produce the large number of separate base cases desirable to implement this strategy efficiently.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The generalized version of this idea is known as recursion "unrolling" or "coarsening", and various techniques have been proposed for automating the procedure of enlarging the base case.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For some problems, the branched recursion may end up evaluating the same sub-problem many times over.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In such cases it may be worth identifying and saving the solutions to these overlapping subproblems, a technique which is commonly known as memoization.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Followed to the limit, it leads to bottom-up divide-and-conquer algorithms such as dynamic programming.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/dutch-national-flag-problem] The **Dutch national flag problem** is a computational problem proposed by Edsger Dijkstra.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/dutch-national-flag-problem] The flag of the Netherlands consists of three colors: red, white, and blue.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/dutch-national-flag-problem] Given balls of these three colors arranged randomly in a line (it does not matter how many balls there are), the task is to arrange them such that all balls of the same color are together and their collective color groups are in the correct order.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/dutch-national-flag-problem] Several solutions exist that have varying performance characteristics, tailored to sorting arrays with either small or large numbers of repeated elements.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/dutch-national-flag-problem] This problem can also be viewed in terms of rearranging elements of an array.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/dutch-national-flag-problem] Suppose each of the possible elements could be classified into exactly one of three categories (bottom, middle, and top).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/dutch-national-flag-problem] For example, if all the elements are in 0 ...
[src:quicksort-algorithm/dutch-national-flag-problem] 1, the bottom could be defined as elements in 0 ...
[src:quicksort-algorithm/dutch-national-flag-problem] 0.5 (not including 0.5) and the top as 0.5 and greater.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/dutch-national-flag-problem] (The choice of these values illustrates that the categories need not be equal ranges).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/dutch-national-flag-problem] The problem is then to produce an array such that all "bottom" elements come before (have an index less than the index of) all "middle" elements, which come before all "top" elements.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/dutch-national-flag-problem] One algorithm is to have the top group grow down from the top of the array, the bottom group grow up from the bottom, and keep the middle group just above the bottom.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/dutch-national-flag-problem] The algorithm indexes three locations, the bottom of the top group, the top of the bottom group, and the top of the middle group.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/dutch-national-flag-problem] Elements that are yet to be sorted fall between the middle and the top group.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/dutch-national-flag-problem] At each step, examine the element just above the middle.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/dutch-national-flag-problem] If it belongs to the top group, swap it with the element just below the top.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/dutch-national-flag-problem] If it belongs in the bottom, swap it with the element just above the bottom.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/dutch-national-flag-problem] Complexity is Θ(n) moves and examinations.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/dutch-national-flag-problem] The following pseudocode for three-way partitioning which assumes zero-based array indexing was proposed by Dijkstra himself.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/dutch-national-flag-problem] It uses three indices i, j and k, maintaining the invariant that *i* ≤ *j* ≤ *k*.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] In computer science, an **in-place algorithm** is an algorithm that operates directly on the input data structure without requiring extra space proportional to the input size.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] In other words, it modifies the input in place, without creating a separate copy of the data structure.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] An algorithm which is not in-place is sometimes called **not-in-place** or **out-of-place**.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] In-place can have slightly different meanings.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] In its strictest form, the algorithm can only have a constant amount of extra space, counting everything including function calls and pointers.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] However, this form is very limited as simply having an index to a length *n* array requires *O*(log *n*) bits.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] More broadly, in-place means that the algorithm does not use extra space for manipulating the input but may require a small though non-constant extra space for its operation.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Usually, this space is *O*(log *n*), though sometimes anything in *o*(*n*) is allowed.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Note that space complexity also has varied choices in whether or not to count the index lengths as part of the space used.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Often, the space complexity is given in terms of the number of indices or pointers needed, ignoring their length.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] In this article, we refer to total space complexity (DSPACE), counting pointer lengths.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Therefore, the space requirements here have an extra log *n* factor compared to an analysis that ignores the lengths of indices and pointers.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] An algorithm may or may not count the output as part of its space usage.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Since in-place algorithms usually overwrite their input with output, no additional space is needed.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] When writing the output to write-only memory or a stream, it may be more appropriate to only consider the working space of the algorithm.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] In theoretical applications such as log-space reductions, it is more typical to always ignore output space (in these cases it is more essential that the output is *write-only*).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Given an array `a` of *n* items, suppose we want an array that holds the same elements in reversed order and to dispose of the original.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] One seemingly simple way to do this is to create a new array of equal size, fill it with copies from `a` in the appropriate order and then delete `a`.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Unfortunately, this requires *O*(*n*) extra space for having the arrays `a` and `b` available simultaneously.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Also, allocation and deallocation are often slow operations.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Since we no longer need `a`, we can instead overwrite it with its own reversal using this in-place algorithm which will only need constant number (2) of integers for the auxiliary variables `i` and `tmp`, no matter how large the array is.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] As another example, many sorting algorithms rearrange arrays into sorted order in-place, including: bubble sort, comb sort, selection sort, insertion sort, heapsort, and Shell sort.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] These algorithms require only a few pointers, so their space complexity is *O*(log *n*).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Quicksort operates in-place on the data to be sorted.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] However, quicksort requires *O*(log *n*) stack space pointers to keep track of the subarrays in its divide and conquer strategy.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Consequently, quicksort needs *O*(log2 *n*) additional space.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Although this non-constant space technically takes quicksort out of the in-place category, quicksort and other algorithms needing only *O*(log *n*) additional pointers are usually considered in-place algorithms.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Most selection algorithms are also in-place, although some considerably rearrange the input array in the process of finding the final, constant-sized result.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Some text manipulation algorithms such as trim and reverse may be done in-place.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] In computational complexity theory, the strict definition of in-place algorithms includes all algorithms with *O*(1) space complexity, the class **DSPACE**(1).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] This class is very limited; it equals the regular languages.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] In fact, it does not even include any of the examples listed above.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Algorithms are usually considered in L, the class of problems requiring *O*(log *n*) additional space, to be in-place.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] This class is more in line with the practical definition, as it allows numbers of size *n* as pointers or indices.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] This expanded definition still excludes quicksort, however, because of its recursive calls.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] This in turn yields in-place algorithms for problems such as determining if a graph is bipartite or testing whether two graphs have the same number of connected components.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] In many cases, the space requirements of an algorithm can be drastically cut by using a randomized algorithm.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] For example, if one wishes to know if two vertices in a graph of *n* vertices are in the same connected component of the graph, there is no known simple, deterministic, in-place algorithm to determine this.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] However, if we simply start at one vertex and perform a random walk of about 20*n*3 steps, the chance that we will stumble across the other vertex provided that it is in the same component is very high.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Similarly, there are simple randomized in-place algorithms for primality testing such as the Miller–Rabin primality test, and there are also simple in-place randomized factoring algorithms such as Pollard's rho algorithm.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Functional programming languages often discourage or do not support explicit in-place algorithms that overwrite data, since this is a type of side effect; instead, they only allow new data to be constructed.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] However, good functional language compilers will often recognize when an object very similar to an existing one is created and then the old one is thrown away, and will optimize this into a simple mutation "under the hood".
[src:quicksort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Note that it is possible in principle to carefully construct in-place algorithms that do not modify data (unless the data is no longer being used), but this is rarely done in practice.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] In computer science, the **median of medians** is an approximate median selection algorithm, frequently used to supply a good pivot for an exact selection algorithm, most commonly quickselect, that selects the *k*th smallest element of an initially unsorted array.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] Median of medians finds an approximate median in linear time.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] Using this approximate median as an improved pivot, the worst-case complexity of quickselect reduces from quadratic to *linear*, which is also the asymptotically optimal worst-case complexity of any selection algorithm.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] In other words, the median of medians is an approximate median-selection algorithm that helps building an asymptotically optimal, exact general selection algorithm (especially in the sense of worst-case complexity), by producing good pivot elements.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] Median of medians can also be used as a pivot strategy in quicksort, yielding an optimal algorithm, with worst-case complexity $O(n\log n)$ .
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] The median of medians algorithm guarantees a worst-case runtime of O(n) by recursively selecting good pivot elements, discarding at least 30% of elements at each step.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] Although this approach optimizes the asymptotic worst-case complexity quite well, it is typically outperformed in practice by instead choosing random pivots for its average $O(n)$ complexity for selection and average $O(n\log n)$ complexity for sorting, without any overhead of computing the pivot.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] Similarly, median of medians is used in the hybrid introselect algorithm as a fallback for pivot selection at each iteration until kth smallest is found.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] Even though asymptotically similar, such a hybrid algorithm will have a lower complexity than a straightforward introselect up to a constant factor (both in average-case and worst-case), at any finite length.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] The algorithm was published in 1973 and is sometimes called **BFPRT** after the last names of the authors (Blum, Floyd, Pratt, Rivest, Tarjan).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] In the original paper, the algorithm was referred to as **PICK**, referring to quickselect as *FIND*.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] Quickselect is linear-time on average, but it can require quadratic time with poor pivot choices.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] This is because quickselect is a divide and conquer algorithm, with each step taking $O(n)$ time in the size of the remaining search set.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] If the search set decreases exponentially quickly in size (by a fixed proportion), this yields a geometric series times the $O(n)$ factor of a single step, and thus linear overall time.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] However, if the search set decreases slowly in size, such as linearly (by a fixed number of elements, in the worst case only reducing by one element each time), then a linear sum of linear steps yields quadratic overall time (formally, triangular numbers grow quadratically).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] For example, the worst-case occurs when pivoting on the smallest element at each step, such as applying quickselect for the maximum element to already sorted data and taking the first element as pivot each time.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] If one instead consistently chooses "good" pivots, this is avoided and one always gets linear performance even in the worst case.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] A "good" pivot is one for which we can establish that a constant proportion of elements fall both below and above it, as then the search set decreases at least by a constant proportion at each step, hence exponentially quickly, and the overall time remains linear.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] The median is a good pivot – the best for sorting, and the best overall choice for selection – decreasing the search set by half at each step.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] Thus if one can compute the median in linear time, this only adds linear time to each step, and thus the overall complexity of the algorithm remains linear.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] The median-of-medians algorithm computes an approximate median, namely a point that is guaranteed to be between the 30th and 70th percentiles (in the middle 4 deciles).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] Thus the search set decreases by at least 30%.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] The problem is reduced to 70% of the original size, which is a fixed proportion smaller.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] As stated before, median-of-medians is used as a pivot selection strategy in the quickselect algorithm, which in pseudocode looks as follows.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] Be careful to handle `left`, `right` and `n` when implementing.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] The following pseudocode assumes that `left`, `right`, and the list use one-based numbering and that `select` is initially called with 1 as the argument to `left` and the length of the list as the argument to `right`.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] Note that this returns the index of the n'th smallest number after rearranging the list, rather than the actual value of the n'th smallest number.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] Subroutine pivot is the actual median-of-medians algorithm.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] It divides its input (a list of length n) into groups of at most five elements, computes the median of each of those groups using some subroutine, then recursively computes the true median of the ${\frac {n}{5}}$ medians found in the previous step:.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] Note that pivot calls select; this is an instance of mutual recursion.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] There is a subroutine called partition that can, in linear time, group a list (ranging from indices `left` to `right`) into three parts, those less than a certain element, those equal to it, and those greater than the element (a three-way partition).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] The grouping into three parts ensures that the median-of-medians maintains linear execution time in a case of many or all coincident elements.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] The partition5 subroutine selects the median of a group of at most five elements; an easy way to implement this is insertion sort, as shown below.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] It can also be implemented as a decision tree.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] Of the ${\frac {n}{5}}$ groups, half the number of groups $\left({\frac {1}{2}}\times {\frac {n}{5}}={\frac {n}{10}}\right)$ have their median less than the pivot (Median of Medians).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] Also, another half the number of groups $\left({\frac {1}{2}}\times {\frac {n}{5}}={\frac {n}{10}}\right)$ , again have their median greater than the pivot.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] In each of the ${\frac {n}{10}}$ groups with median less than the pivot, there are two elements that are smaller than their respective medians, which are smaller than the pivot.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] Thus, each of the ${\frac {n}{10}}$ groups have at least 3 elements that are smaller than the pivot.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] Similarly, in each of the ${\frac {n}{10}}$ groups with median greater than the pivot, there are two elements that are greater than their respective medians, which are greater than the pivot.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] Thus, each of the ${\frac {n}{10}}$ groups have at least 3 elements that are greater than the pivot.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] Hence, the pivot is less than $3\times {\frac {n}{10}}$ elements and greater than another $3\times {\frac {n}{10}}$ elements.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] Thus the chosen median splits the ordered elements somewhere between 30%/70% and 70%/30%, which assures worst-case linear behavior of the algorithm.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] 5-tuples are shown here sorted by median, for clarity.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] Sorting the tuples is not necessary because we only need the median for use as pivot element.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] Note that all elements above/left of the red (30% of the 100 elements) are less, and all elements below/right of the red (another 30% of the 100 elements) are greater.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] The median-calculating recursive call does not exceed worst-case linear behavior because the list of medians has size ${\frac {n}{5}}$ , while the other recursive call recurses on at most 70% of the list.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] Let $T(n)$ be the time it takes to run a median-of-medians Quickselect algorithm on an array of size n .
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] By induction: Assume $\exists c'\in \mathbb {R} _{+}$ such that $\forall k<n$ it $T(k)\leq c'\cdot k$ holds.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] The key step is reducing the problem to selecting in two lists whose total length is shorter than the original list, plus a linear factor for the reduction step.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] This allows a simple induction to show that the overall running time is linear.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] The specific choice of groups of five elements is explained as follows.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] Firstly, computing median of an odd list is faster and simpler; while one could use an even list, this requires taking the average of the two middle elements, which is slower than simply selecting the single exact middle element.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] Secondly, five is the smallest odd number such that median of medians works.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] With groups of only three elements, the resulting list of medians to search in is length ${\frac {n}{3}}$ , and reduces the list to recurse into length ${\frac {2}{3}}n$ , since it is greater than 1/2 × 2/3 = 1/3 of the elements and less than 1/2 × 2/3 = 1/3 of the elements.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] Thus this still leaves n elements to search in, not reducing the problem sufficiently.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] The individual lists are shorter, however, and one can bound the resulting complexity to $O(n\log n)$ by the Akra–Bazzi method, but it does not prove linearity.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] Conversely, one may instead group by g = seven, nine, or more elements, and this does work.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] This reduces the size of the list of medians to ${\frac {n}{g}}$ *,* and the size of the list to recurse into asymptotes at 3*n*/4 (75%), as the quadrants in the above table approximate 25%, as the size of the overlapping lines decreases proportionally.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] This reduces the scaling factor from 10 asymptotically to 4, but accordingly raises the c term for the partitioning work.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] Finding the median of a larger group takes longer, but is a constant factor (depending only on g ), and thus does not change the overall performance as *n* grows.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] In fact, considering the number of comparisons in the worst case, the constant factor is ${\frac {2g(g-1)}{g-3}}$ and this is minimized over odd integers greater than three at 20 when $g=5$ .
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] As with grouping by 3, the individual lists are shorter, but the overall length is no shorter – in fact longer – and thus one can only prove superlinear bounds.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/median-of-medians] Grouping into a square of ${\sqrt {n}}$ lists of length ${\sqrt {n}}$ is similarly complicated.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] A **partition** is a division of a logical database or its constituent elements into distinct independent parts.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] Database partitioning refers to intentionally breaking a large database into smaller ones for scalability purposes, distinct from network partitions which are a type of network fault between nodes.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] In a partitioned database, each piece of data belongs to exactly one partition, effectively making each partition a small database of its own.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] Database partitioning is normally done for manageability, performance or availability reasons, or for load balancing.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] It is popular in distributed database management systems, where each partition may be spread over multiple nodes, with users at the node performing local transactions on the partition.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] This increases performance for sites that have regular transactions involving certain views of data, whilst maintaining availability and security.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] Partitioning enables distribution of datasets across multiple disks and query loads across multiple processors.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] For queries that operate on a single partition, each node executes queries independently on its local partition, enabling linear scaling of query throughput with additional nodes.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] More complex queries can be parallelized across multiple nodes, though this presents additional challenges.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] Database partitioning emerged in the 1980s with systems like Teradata and NonStop SQL.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] The approach was later adopted by NoSQL databases and Hadoop-based data warehouses.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] While implementations vary between transactional and analytical workloads, the core principles of partitioning remain consistent across both use cases.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] Partitioning is commonly implemented alongside replication, storing partition copies across multiple nodes.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] Each record belongs to one partition but may exist on multiple nodes for fault tolerance.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] In leader-follower replication systems, nodes can simultaneously serve as leaders for some partitions and followers for others.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] Partitioning aims to distribute data and query load evenly across nodes.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] With ideal distribution, system capacity scales linearly with added nodes—ten nodes should process ten times the data and throughput of a single node.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] Uneven distribution, termed *skew*, reduces partitioning efficiency.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] Partitions with excessive load are called *hot spots*.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] Current high-end relational database management systems provide for different criteria to split the database.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] They take a *partitioning key* and assign a partition based on certain criteria.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] In any partitioning scheme, data is typically arranged so that each piece of data (record, row, or document) belongs to exactly one partition.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] While some databases support operations that span multiple partitions, this single-partition association is fundamental to the partitioning concept.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] The partitioning can be done by either building separate smaller databases (each with its own tables, indices, and transaction logs), or by splitting selected elements, for example just one table.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] Horizontal partitioning involves putting different rows into different tables.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] For example, customers with ZIP codes less than 50000 are stored in CustomersEast, while customers with ZIP codes greater than or equal to 50000 are stored in CustomersWest.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] The two partition tables are then CustomersEast and CustomersWest, while a view with a union might be created over both of them to provide a complete view of all customers.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] Vertical partitioning involves creating tables with fewer columns and using additional tables to store the remaining columns.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] Generally, this practice is known as normalization.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] However, vertical partitioning extends further, and partitions columns even when already normalized.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] This type of partitioning is also called "row splitting", since rows get split by their columns, and might be performed explicitly or implicitly.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] Distinct physical machines might be used to realize vertical partitioning: storing infrequently used or very wide columns, taking up a significant amount of memory, on a different machine, for example, is a method of vertical partitioning.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] A common form of vertical partitioning is to split static data from dynamic data, since the former is faster to access than the latter, particularly for a table where the dynamic data is not used as often as the static.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] Creating a view across the two newly created tables restores the original table with a performance penalty, but accessing the static data alone will show higher performance.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/partition-database] A columnar database can be regarded as a database that has been vertically partitioned until each column is stored in its own table.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quickselect] In computer science, **quickselect** is a selection algorithm to find the *k*th smallest element in an unordered list, also known as the *k*th order statistic.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quickselect] Like the related quicksort sorting algorithm, it was developed by Tony Hoare, and thus is also known as **Hoare's selection algorithm**.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quickselect] Like quicksort, it is efficient in practice and has good average-case performance, but has poor worst-case performance.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quickselect] Quickselect and its variants are the selection algorithms most often used in efficient real-world implementations.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quickselect] Quickselect uses the same overall approach as quicksort, choosing one element as a pivot and partitioning the data in two based on the pivot, accordingly as less than or greater than the pivot.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quickselect] However, instead of recursing into both sides, as in quicksort, quickselect only recurses into one side – the side with the element it is searching for.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quickselect] This reduces the average complexity from $O(n\log n)$ to $O(n)$ , with a worst case of $O(n^{2})$ .
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quickselect] As with quicksort, quickselect is generally implemented as an in-place algorithm, and beyond selecting the kth element, it also partially sorts the data.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quickselect] See selection algorithm for further discussion of the connection with sorting.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quickselect] In quicksort, there is a subprocedure called `partition` that can, in linear time, group a list (ranging from indices `left` to `right`) into two parts: those less than a certain element, and those greater than or equal to the element.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quickselect] This is known as the Lomuto partition scheme, which is simpler but less efficient than Hoare's original partition scheme.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quickselect] In quicksort, we recursively sort both branches, leading to best-case $O(n\log n)$ time.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quickselect] However, when doing selection, we already know which partition our desired element lies in, since the pivot is in its final sorted position, with all those preceding it in an unsorted order and all those following it in an unsorted order.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quickselect] Just as the minimum-based selection algorithm is a partial selection sort, this is a partial quicksort, generating and partitioning only $O(\log n)$ of its $O(n)$ partitions.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quickselect] This simple procedure has expected linear performance, and, like quicksort, has quite good performance in practice.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quickselect] This `select` function works only with the Lomuto partition scheme.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quickselect] This is because `select` assumes that the return value from partition is the position of the pivot.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quickselect] This is true for the Lomuto partition scheme, but not for the Hoare's partition scheme.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quickselect] In Hoare's scheme, the return value is the last index of the "left" partition, and the pivot is not guaranteed to be "in between" the partitions.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quickselect] The recursion, as presented, also only works with Lomuto's scheme, as it assumes that the right partition starts with `pivotIndex +1`, while when using Hoare's scheme, the right partition starts at `pivotIndex`.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quickselect] Like quicksort, quickselect has good average performance, but is sensitive to the pivot that is chosen.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quickselect] However, if bad pivots are consistently chosen, such as decreasing by only a single element each time, then worst-case performance is quadratic: $O(n^{2}).$ This occurs, for example, in searching for the maximum element of a set, using the first element as the pivot, and having sorted data.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quickselect] However, for randomly chosen pivots, this worst case is very unlikely: the probability of using more than $Cn$ comparisons, for any sufficiently large constant C , is superexponentially small as a function of C .
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quickselect] The easiest solution is to choose a random pivot, which yields almost certain linear time.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quickselect] Deterministically, one can use the median-of-3 pivot strategy (as in Quicksort), which yields linear performance on partially sorted data, as is common in the real world.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quickselect] However, contrived sequences can still cause worst-case complexity; David Musser describes a "median-of-3 killer" sequence that allows an attack against that strategy, which was one motivation for his introselect algorithm.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quickselect] One can assure linear performance even in the worst case by using a more sophisticated pivot strategy; this is done in the median of medians algorithm.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quickselect] However, the overhead of computing the pivot is high, and thus, this is generally not used in practice.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quickselect] One can combine basic quickselect with median of medians as a fallback to get both fast average case performance and linear worst-case performance; this is done in introselect.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quickselect] Finer computations of the average time complexity yield a worst case of $n(2+2\log 2+o(1))\leq 3.4n+o(n)$ for random pivots (in the case of the median; other *k* are faster).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quickselect] The constant can be improved to 3/2 by a more complicated pivot strategy, yielding the Floyd–Rivest algorithm, which has average complexity of $1.5n+O(n^{1/2})$ for median, with other *k* being faster.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Quicksort is a divide-and-conquer algorithm.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] It works by selecting a "pivot" element from the array and partitioning the other elements into two sub-arrays, according to whether they are less than or greater than the pivot.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] For this reason, it is sometimes called **partition-exchange sort**.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] The sub-arrays are then sorted recursively.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] This can be done in-place, requiring small additional amounts of memory to perform the sorting.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Quicksort is a comparison sort, meaning that it can sort items of any type for which a "less-than" relation (formally, a total order) is defined.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] It is a comparison-based sort since elements *a* and *b* are only swapped in case their relative order has been obtained in the transitive closure of prior comparison-outcomes.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Most implementations of quicksort are not stable, meaning that the relative order of equal sort items is not preserved.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Mathematical analysis of quicksort shows that, on average, the algorithm takes $O(n\log {n})$ comparisons to sort *n* items.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] In the worst case, it makes $O(n^{2})$ comparisons.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] The quicksort algorithm was developed in 1959 by Tony Hoare while he was a visiting student at Moscow State University.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] At that time, Hoare was working on a machine translation project for the National Physical Laboratory.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] As a part of the translation process, he needed to sort the words in Russian sentences before looking them up in a Russian-English dictionary, which was in alphabetical order on magnetic tape.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] After recognizing that his first idea, insertion sort, would be slow, he came up with a new idea.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] He wrote the partition part in Mercury Autocode but had trouble dealing with the list of unsorted segments.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] On return to England, he was asked to write code for Shellsort.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Hoare mentioned to his boss that he knew of a faster algorithm, and his boss bet a sixpence that he did not.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] His boss ultimately accepted that he had lost the bet.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Hoare published a paper about his algorithm, including a theoretical analysis, in The Computer Journal Volume 5, Issue 1, 1962, Pages 10–16.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Later, Hoare learned about ALGOL and its ability to do recursion, which enabled him to publish an improved version of the algorithm in ALGOL in *Communications of the Association for Computing Machinery*, the premier computer science journal of the time.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] The ALGOL code is published in Communications of the ACM (CACM), Volume 4, Issue 7 July 1961, pp 321 Algorithm 63: partition and Algorithm 64: Quicksort.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Quicksort gained widespread adoption, appearing, for example, in Unix as the default library sort subroutine.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Hence, it lent its name to the C standard library subroutine qsort and in the reference implementation of Java.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Bentley described another simpler and compact partitioning scheme in his book *Programming Pearls* that he attributed to Nico Lomuto.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Later Bentley wrote that he used Hoare's version for years but never really understood it but Lomuto's version was simple enough to prove correct.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Bentley described Quicksort as the "most beautiful code I had ever written" in the same essay.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Lomuto's partition scheme was also popularized by the textbook *Introduction to Algorithms* although it is inferior to Hoare's scheme because it does three times more swaps on average and degrades to *O*(*n*2) runtime when all elements are equal.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] McIlroy would further produce an *AntiQuicksort* (aqsort) function in 1998, which consistently drives even his 1993 variant of Quicksort into quadratic behavior by producing adversarial data on-the-fly.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Quicksort is a type of divide-and-conquer algorithm for sorting an array, based on a partitioning routine; the details of this partitioning can vary somewhat, so that quicksort is really a family of closely related algorithms.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Applied to a range of at least two elements, partitioning produces a division into two consecutive non-empty sub-ranges, in such a way that no element of the first sub-range is greater than any element of the second sub-range.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] After applying this partition, quicksort then recursively sorts the sub-ranges, possibly after excluding from them an element at the point of division that is at this point known to be already in its final location.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Due to its recursive nature, quicksort (like the partition routine) has to be formulated so as to be callable for a range within a larger array, even if the ultimate goal is to sort a complete array.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] (Optional) If the range is very short, use a special-purpose sorting method, and return.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] For example, ranges of two elements can be sorted with a single comparison.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Otherwise select a value, called a *pivot*, which occurs in the range.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] *Partition* the range: reorder its elements into sub-ranges, so that all elements with values less than the pivot are in the first sub-range, while all elements with values greater than the pivot are in the second.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Elements with values equal to the pivot may be placed in either sub-range, or in a third sub-range between the other two.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] This middle sub-range is optional, but quicksort requires that the first two sub-ranges are each strictly smaller than the original range, which is most easily achieved by placing at least one pivot element in the middle.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Recursively apply quicksort to the two sub-ranges, excluding the middle sub-range which is already in its final position.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] These are the basic requirement for correct operation.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Details not specified above, including the partition algorithm, and particularly the pivot selection, can greatly affect the algorithm's performance for some input arrays.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] To discuss the efficiency of quicksort, it is therefore necessary to specify these choices first.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Here, we mention two specific partition methods.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] This scheme is attributed to Nico Lomuto and popularized by Bentley in his book *Programming Pearls* and Cormen *et al.* in their book *Introduction to Algorithms*.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] In most formulations, this scheme chooses as the pivot the last element in the array.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] The algorithm maintains index i as it scans the array using another index j such that the elements at lo through i−1 (inclusive) are less than the pivot, and the elements at i through j (inclusive) are equal to or greater than the pivot.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] As this scheme is more compact and easier to understand, it is frequently used in introductory material, although it is less efficient than Hoare's original scheme, e.g., when all elements are equal.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] The complexity of Quicksort with this scheme degrades to *O*(*n*2) when the array is already in order, due to the partition being the worst possible one.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] There have been various variants proposed to boost performance, including various ways to select the pivot, deal with equal elements, use other sorting algorithms such as insertion sort for small arrays, and so on.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Sorting the entire array is accomplished by quicksort(A, 0, length(A) - 1).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] With this formulation, it is possible that one sub-range turns out to be the whole original range, which would prevent the algorithm from advancing.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] With respect to this original description, implementations often make minor but important variations.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] While there is no reason to exchange elements equal to the pivot, this change allows tests on the pointers themselves to be omitted, which are otherwise needed to ensure they do not run out of range.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] (The latter is true independently of the test used, so it would be possible to use the inclusive test only when looking for the first inversion.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Such a separation can only result when no inversions are found, with both pointers advancing to the pivot element at the first iteration (they are then considered to have crossed, and no exchange takes place).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] The entire array is sorted by quicksort(A, 0, length(A) - 1).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Hoare's scheme is more efficient than Lomuto's partition scheme because it does three times fewer swaps on average.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Also, as mentioned, the implementation given creates a balanced partition even when all values are equal., which Lomuto's scheme does not.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Like Lomuto's partition scheme, Hoare's partitioning also would cause Quicksort to degrade to *O*(*n*2) for already sorted input, if the pivot was chosen as the first or the last element.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] With the middle element as the pivot, however, sorted data results with (almost) no swaps in equally sized partitions leading to best case behavior of Quicksort, i.e.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Like others, Hoare's partitioning doesn't produce a stable sort.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Therefore, the next two segments that the main algorithm recurs on are (lo..p) (elements ≤ pivot) and (p+1..hi) (elements ≥ pivot) as opposed to (lo..p−1) and (p+1..hi) as in Lomuto's scheme.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Let us expand a little bit on the next two segments that the main algorithm recurs on.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Because we are using strict comparators (>, <) in the **"do...while"** loops to prevent ourselves from running out of range, there's a chance that the pivot itself gets swapped with other elements in the partition function.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] With this example, we see how it is necessary to include the returned index of the partition function in our subsequent recursions.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] As a result, we are presented with the choices of either recursing on (lo..p) and (p+1..hi), or (lo..p−1) and (p..hi).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Which of the two options we choose depends on which index (**i** or **j**) we return in the partition function when the indices cross, and how we choose our pivot in the partition function (**floor** v.s.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] First, examine the choice of recursing on (lo..p) and (p+1..hi), with the example of sorting an array where multiple identical elements exist **[0, 0]**.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] If index i (the "latter" index) is returned after indices cross in the partition function, the index 1 would be returned after the first partition.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] The subsequent recursion on (lo..p) would be on (0, 1), which corresponds to the same array **[0, 0]**.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] A non-advancing separation that causes infinite recursion is produced.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] It is for the same reason why the choice of the last element as the pivot must be avoided.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] The choice of recursing on (lo..p−1) and (p..hi) follows the same logic as above.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] The two nuances are clear, again, when considering the examples of sorting an array where multiple identical elements exist (**[0, 0]**), and an already sorted array **[0, 1]** respectively.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] It is noteworthy that with this version of recursion, for the same reason, the choice of the first element as pivot must be avoided.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] In the very early versions of quicksort, the leftmost element of the partition would often be chosen as the pivot element.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Unfortunately, this causes worst-case behavior on already sorted arrays, which is a rather common use case.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] The problem was easily solved by choosing either a random index for the pivot, choosing the middle index of the partition or (especially for longer partitions) choosing the median of the first, middle and last element of the partition for the pivot (as recommended by Sedgewick).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] This "median-of-three" rule counters the case of sorted (or reverse-sorted) input, and gives a better estimate of the optimal pivot (the true median) than selecting any single element, when no information about the ordering of the input is known.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] It puts a median into `A[hi]` first, then that new value of `A[hi]` is used for a pivot, as in a basic algorithm presented above.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Specifically, the expected number of comparisons needed to sort n elements (see § Average-case analysis) with random pivot selection is 1.386 *n* log *n*.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Median-of-three pivoting brings this down to *C**n*, 2 ≈ 1.188 *n* log *n*, at the expense of a three-percent increase in the expected number of swaps.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Selecting a pivot element is also complicated by the existence of integer overflow.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] If the boundary indices of the subarray being sorted are sufficiently large, the naïve expression for the middle index, (*lo* + *hi*)/2, will cause overflow and provide an invalid pivot index.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] This can be overcome by using, for example, *lo* + (*hi*−*lo*)/2 to index the middle element, at the cost of more complex arithmetic.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Similar issues arise in some other methods of selecting the pivot element.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] With a partitioning algorithm such as the Lomuto partition scheme described above (even one that chooses good pivot values), quicksort exhibits poor performance for inputs that contain many repeated elements.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] The problem is clearly apparent when all the input elements are equal: at each recursion, the left partition is empty (no input values are less than the pivot), and the right partition has only decreased by one element (the pivot is removed).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Consequently, the Lomuto partition scheme takes quadratic time to sort an array of equal values.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] In the case where all elements are equal, the Hoare partition scheme needlessly swaps elements, but the partitioning itself is best case, as noted in the Hoare partition section above.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] To solve the Lomuto partition scheme problem (sometimes called the Dutch national flag problem), an alternative linear-time partition routine can be used that separates the values into three groups: values less than the pivot, values equal to the pivot, and values greater than the pivot.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] (Bentley and McIlroy call this a "fat partition" and it was already implemented in the qsort of Version 7 Unix.) The values equal to the pivot are already sorted, so only the less-than and greater-than partitions need to be recursively sorted.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] The `partition` algorithm returns indices to the first ('leftmost') and to the last ('rightmost') item of the middle partition.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Every other item of the partition is equal to the pivot and is therefore sorted.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Consequently, the items of the partition need not be included in the recursive calls to `quicksort`.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] The best case for the algorithm now occurs when all elements are equal (or are chosen from a small set of *k* ≪ *n* elements).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] In the case of all equal elements, the modified quicksort will perform only two recursive calls on empty subarrays and thus finish in linear time (assuming the `partition` subroutine takes no longer than linear time).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Quicksort's divide-and-conquer formulation makes it amenable to parallelization using task parallelism.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] The partitioning step is accomplished through the use of a parallel prefix sum algorithm to compute an index for each array element in its section of the partitioned array.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Given an array of size n, the partitioning step performs O(*n*) work in *O*(log *n*) time and requires O(*n*) additional scratch space.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] After the array has been partitioned, the two partitions can be sorted recursively in parallel.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Assuming an ideal choice of pivots, parallel quicksort sorts an array of size n in O(*n* log *n*) work in O(log2 *n*) time using O(*n*) additional space.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Quicksort has some disadvantages when compared to alternative sorting algorithms, like merge sort, which complicate its efficient parallelization.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] The depth of quicksort's divide-and-conquer tree directly impacts the algorithm's scalability, and this depth is highly dependent on the algorithm's choice of pivot.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Additionally, it is difficult to parallelize the partitioning step efficiently in-place.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] The use of scratch space simplifies the partitioning step, but increases the algorithm's memory footprint and constant overheads.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Other, more sophisticated parallel sorting algorithms can achieve even better time bounds.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] For example, in 1991 David M W Powers described a parallelized quicksort (and a related radix sort) that can operate in *O*(log *n*) time on a CRCW (concurrent read and concurrent write) PRAM (parallel random-access machine) with n processors by performing partitioning implicitly.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] The most unbalanced partition occurs when one of the sublists returned by the partitioning routine is of size *n* − 1.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] This may occur if the pivot happens to be the smallest or largest element in the list, or in some implementations (e.g., the Lomuto partition scheme as described above) when all the elements are equal.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] If this happens repeatedly in every partition, then each recursive call processes a list of size one less than the previous list.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Consequently, it takes *n* − 1 nested calls before reaching a list of size 1.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] This means that the call tree is a linear chain of *n* − 1 nested calls.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] The ith call does *O*(*n* − *i*) work to do the partition, and $\textstyle \sum _{i=0}^{n}(n-i)=O(n^{2})$ , so in that case quicksort takes *O*(*n*2) time.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] In the most balanced case, each partition divides the list into two nearly equal pieces.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] This means each recursive call processes a list of half the size.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Consequently, only log2 *n* nested calls can be made before reaching a list of size 1.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] This means that the depth of the call tree is log2 *n*.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] But no two calls at the same level of the call tree process the same part of the original list; thus, each level of calls needs only *O*(*n*) time all together (each call has some constant overhead, but since there are only *O*(*n*) calls at each level, this is subsumed in the *O*(*n*) factor).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] The result is that the algorithm uses only *O*(*n* log *n*) time.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] To sort an array of n distinct elements, quicksort takes *O*(*n* log *n*) time in expectation, averaged over all *n*! permutations of n elements with equal probability.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Three common proofs of this claim use percentiles, recurrences, and binary search trees, each providing different insights into quicksort's workings.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] If each pivot has rank somewhere in the middle 50 percent, that is, between the 25th percentile and the 75th percentile, then it splits the elements with at least 25% and at most 75% on each side.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Consistently choosing such pivots would only have to split the list at most $\log _{4/3}n$ times before reaching lists of size 1, yielding an *O*(*n* log *n*) algorithm.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] When the input is a random permutation, the pivot has a random rank, and so it is not guaranteed to be in the middle 50%.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] However, when starting from a random permutation, each recursive call's pivot has a random rank in its list, and therefore is in the middle 50% approximately half the time.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Imagine that a coin is flipped: heads means that the rank of the pivot is in the middle 50%, tails means that it is not.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Now imagine that the coin is flipped over and over until it gets k heads.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Although this could take a long time, on average only 2*k* flips are required, and the chance that the coin will not obtain k heads after 100*k* flips is highly improbable (this can be made rigorous using Chernoff bounds).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] By the same argument, Quicksort's recursion will terminate on average at a call depth of only $2\log _{4/3}n$ .
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] But if its average call depth is *O*(log *n*), and each level of the call tree processes at most n elements, the total amount of work done on average is the product, *O*(*n* log *n*).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] The algorithm does not have to verify that the pivot is in the middle half as long as it is a consistent number of times.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] An alternative approach is to set up a recurrence relation for the *T*(*n*) factor, the time needed to sort a list of size n.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] This is the same relation as for insertion sort and selection sort, and it solves to worst case *T*(*n*) = *O*(*n*2).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] The master theorem for divide-and-conquer recurrences tells us that *T*(*n*) = *O*(*n* log *n*).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] The outline of a formal proof of the *O*(*n* log *n*) expected time complexity follows.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Assume that there are no duplicates, as duplicates could be handled with linear time pre- and post-processing, or considered cases easier than the analyzed.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] When the input is a random permutation, the rank of the pivot is uniformly random from 0 to *n* − 1.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Then the resulting parts of the partition have sizes i and *n* − *i* − 1, and i is uniform random from 0 to *n* − 1.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] This means that, on average, quicksort performs only about 39% worse than in its best case.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] In this sense, it is closer to the best case than the worst case.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] A comparison sort cannot use less than log2(*n*!) comparisons on average to sort n items (as explained in the article Comparison sort) and in case of large n, Stirling's approximation yields log2(*n*!) ≈ *n*(log2 *n* − log2 *e*), so quicksort is not much worse than an ideal comparison sort.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] This fast average runtime is another reason for quicksort's practical dominance over other sorting algorithms.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] The following binary search tree (BST) corresponds to each execution of quicksort: the initial pivot is the root node; the pivot of the left half is the root of the left subtree, the pivot of the right half is the root of the right subtree, and so on.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] The number of comparisons of the execution of quicksort equals the number of comparisons during the construction of the BST by a sequence of insertions.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] So, the average number of comparisons for randomized quicksort equals the average cost of constructing a BST when the values inserted $(x_{1},x_{2},\ldots ,x_{n})$ form a random permutation.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Consider a BST created by the insertion of a sequence $(x_{1},x_{2},\ldots ,x_{n})$ of values forming a random permutation.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Let C denote the cost of creation of the BST.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] We have $C=\sum _{i}\sum _{j<i}c_{i,j}$ , where $c_{i,j}$ is a binary random variable expressing whether during the insertion of $x_{i}$ there was a comparison to $x_{j}$ .
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] By linearity of expectation, the expected value $\operatorname {E} [C]$ of C is $\operatorname {E} [C]=\sum _{i}\sum _{j<i}\Pr(c_{i,j})$ .
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] The core structural observation is that $x_{i}$ is compared to $x_{j}$ in the algorithm if and only if $x_{i}$ falls inside one of the two intervals adjacent to $x_{j}$ .
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] The space used by quicksort depends on the version used.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] The in-place version of quicksort has a space complexity of *O*(log *n*), even in the worst case, when it is carefully implemented using the following strategies.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Quicksort with in-place and unstable partitioning uses only constant additional space before making any recursive call.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Quicksort must store a constant amount of information for each nested recursive call.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Since the best case makes at most *O*(log *n*) nested recursive calls, it uses *O*(log *n*) space.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] However, without Sedgewick's trick to limit the recursive calls, in the worst case, quicksort could make *O*(*n*) nested recursive calls and need *O*(*n*) auxiliary space.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] From a bit complexity viewpoint, variables such as *lo* and *hi* do not use constant space; it takes *O*(log *n*) bits to index into a list of n items.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Because there are such variables in every stack frame, quicksort using Sedgewick's trick requires *O*((log *n*)2) bits of space.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] This space requirement isn't too terrible, though, since if the list contained distinct elements, it would need at least *O*(*n* log *n*) bits of space.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Stack-free versions of Quicksort have been proposed.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] These use $O(1)$ additional space (more precisely, one cell of the type of the sorted records, in order to exchange records, and a constant number of integer variables used as indices).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Another, less common, not-in-place version of quicksort uses *O*(*n*) space for working storage and can implement a stable sort.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] The working storage allows the input array to be easily partitioned in a stable way and then copied back to the input array for successive recursive calls.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p01] Sedgewick's optimization is still appropriate.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] Quicksort is a space-optimized version of the binary tree sort.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] Instead of inserting items sequentially into an explicit tree, quicksort organizes them concurrently into a tree that is implied by the recursive calls.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] The algorithms make exactly the same comparisons, but in a different order.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] An often desirable property of a sorting algorithm is stability – that is, the order of elements that compare equal is not changed, allowing controlling order of multikey tables (e.g., directory or folder listings) in a natural way.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] This property is hard to maintain for in-place quicksort (that uses only constant additional space for pointers and buffers, and *O*(log *n*) additional space for the management of explicit or implicit recursion).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] For variant quicksorts involving extra memory due to representations using pointers (e.g., lists or trees) or files (effectively lists), it is trivial to maintain stability.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] The more complex, or disk-bound, data structures tend to increase time cost, in general, making increasing use of virtual memory or disk.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] The most direct competitor of quicksort is heapsort.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] Heapsort has the advantages of simplicity and a worst-case run time of *O*(*n* log *n*), but heapsort's *average* running time is usually considered slower than in-place quicksort, primarily due to its worse locality of reference.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] This result is debatable; some publications indicate the opposite.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] The main disadvantage of quicksort is the implementation complexity required to avoid bad pivot choices and the resultant *O*(*n*2) performance.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] Introsort is a variant of quicksort that solves this problem by switching to heapsort when a bad case is detected.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] Major programming languages, such as C++ (in the GNU and LLVM implementations), use introsort.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] Quicksort also competes with merge sort, another *O*(*n* log *n*) sorting algorithm.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] Merge sort's main advantages are that it is a stable sort and has excellent worst-case performance.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] The main disadvantage of merge sort is that it is an out-of-place algorithm, so when operating on arrays, efficient implementations require *O*(*n*) auxiliary space (vs.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] *O*(log *n*) for quicksort with in-place partitioning and tail recursion, or *O*(1) for heapsort).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] Merge sort works very well on linked lists, requiring only a small, constant amount of auxiliary storage.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] Although quicksort *can* be implemented as a stable sort using linked lists, there is no reason to; it will often suffer from poor pivot choices without random access, and is essentially always inferior to merge sort.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] Merge sort is also the algorithm of choice for external sorting of very large data sets stored on slow-to-access media such as disk storage or network-attached storage.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] Bucket sort with two buckets is very similar to quicksort; the pivot in this case is effectively the value in the middle of the value range, which does well on average for uniformly distributed inputs.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] A selection algorithm chooses the kth smallest of a list of numbers; this is an easier problem in general than sorting.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] One simple but effective selection algorithm works nearly in the same manner as quicksort, and is accordingly known as quickselect.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] The difference is that instead of making recursive calls on both sublists, it only makes a single tail-recursive call on the sublist that contains the desired element.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] This change lowers the average complexity to linear or *O*(*n*) time, which is optimal for selection, but the selection algorithm is still *O*(*n*2) in the worst case.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] A variant of quickselect, the median of medians algorithm, chooses pivots more carefully, ensuring that the pivots are near the middle of the data (between the 30th and 70th percentiles), and thus has guaranteed linear time – *O*(*n*).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] This same pivot strategy can be used to construct a variant of quicksort (median of medians quicksort) with *O*(*n* log *n*) time.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] However, the overhead of choosing the pivot is significant, so this is generally not used in practice.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] More abstractly, given an *O*(*n*) selection algorithm, one can use it to find the ideal pivot (the median) at every step of quicksort and thus produce a sorting algorithm with *O*(*n* log *n*) running time.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] Practical implementations of this variant are considerably slower on average, but they are of theoretical interest because they show an optimal selection algorithm can yield an optimal sorting algorithm.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] Instead of partitioning into two subarrays using a single pivot, multi-pivot quicksort (also multiquicksort) partitions its input into some s number of subarrays using *s* − 1 pivots.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] While the dual-pivot case (*s* = 3) was considered by Sedgewick and others already in the mid-1970s, the resulting algorithms were not faster in practice than the "classical" quicksort.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] A 1999 assessment of a multiquicksort with a variable number of pivots, tuned to make efficient use of processor caches, found it to increase the instruction count by some 20%, but simulation results suggested that it would be more efficient on very large inputs.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] A version of dual-pivot quicksort developed by Yaroslavskiy in 2009 turned out to be fast enough to warrant implementation in Java 7, as the standard algorithm to sort arrays of primitives (sorting arrays of objects is done using Timsort).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] The performance benefit of this algorithm was subsequently found to be mostly related to cache performance, and experimental results indicate that the three-pivot variant may perform even better on modern machines.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] For disk files, an external sort based on partitioning similar to quicksort is possible.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] It is slower than external merge sort, but doesn't require extra disk space.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] 4 buffers are used, 2 for input, 2 for output.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] Let $N=$ the number of records in the file, $B=$ the number of records per buffer, and $M=N/B=$ the number of buffer segments in the file.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] Data is read (and written) from both ends of the file inwards.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] Let X represent the segments that start at the beginning of the file, and Y represent segments that start at the end of the file.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] Data is read into the X and Y read buffers.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] A pivot record is chosen and the records in the X and Y buffers other than the pivot record are copied to the X write buffer in ascending order and Y write buffer in descending order based comparison with the pivot record.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] Once either X or Y buffer is filled, it is written to the file, and the next X or Y buffer is read from the file.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] The process continues until all segments are read and one write buffer remains.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] If that buffer is an X write buffer, the pivot record is appended to it and the X buffer is written.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] If that buffer is a Y write buffer, the pivot record is prepended to the Y buffer and the Y buffer written.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] This constitutes one partition step of the file, and the file is now composed of two subfiles.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] The start and end positions of each subfile are pushed/popped to a stand-alone stack or the main stack via recursion.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] To limit stack space to $O(\log _{2}(n))$ , the smaller subfile is processed first.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] For a stand-alone stack, push the larger subfile parameters onto the stack, iterate on the smaller subfile.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] For recursion, recurse on the smaller subfile first, then iterate to handle the larger subfile.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] Once a sub-file is less than or equal to 4 B records, the subfile is sorted in-place via quicksort and written.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] That subfile is now sorted and in place in the file.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] The process is continued until all sub-files are sorted and in place.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] The average number of passes on the file is approximately ${\frac {1+\ln(N+1)}{(4B)}}$ , but worst case pattern is N passes (equivalent to $O(n^{2})$ for worst case internal sort).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] This algorithm is a combination of radix sort and quicksort.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] Pick an element from the array (the pivot) and consider the first character (key) of the string (multikey).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] Partition the remaining elements into three sets: those whose corresponding character is less than, equal to, and greater than the pivot's character.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] Recursively sort the "less than" and "greater than" partitions on the same character.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] Recursively sort the "equal to" partition by the next character (key).
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] Given we sort using bytes or words of length W bits, the best case is *O*(*KN*) and the worst case *O*(2*K**N*) or at least *O*(*N*2) as for standard quicksort, given for unique keys *N*<2*K*, and K is a hidden constant in all standard comparison sort algorithms including quicksort.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] This is a kind of three-way quicksort in which the middle partition represents a (trivially) sorted subarray of elements that are *exactly* equal to the pivot.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] Also developed by Powers as an *O*(*K*) parallel PRAM algorithm.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] This is again a combination of radix sort and quicksort, but the quicksort left/right partition decision is made on successive bits of the key, and is thus *O*(*KN*) for N K-bit keys.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] All comparison sort algorithms implicitly assume the transdichotomous model with K in *Θ*(log *N*), as if K is smaller we can sort in *O*(*N*) time using a hash table or integer sorting.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] If *K* ≫ log *N* but elements are unique within *O*(log *N*) bits, the remaining bits will not be looked at by either quicksort or quick radix sort.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] See Powers for further discussion of the hidden overheads in comparison, radix, and parallel sorting.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] In any comparison-based sorting algorithm, minimizing the number of comparisons requires maximizing the amount of information gained from each comparison, meaning that the comparison results are unpredictable.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] This causes frequent branch mispredictions, limiting performance.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] BlockQuicksort rearranges the computations of quicksort to convert unpredictable branches to data dependencies.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] When partitioning, the input is divided into moderate-sized blocks (which fit easily into the data cache), and two arrays are filled with the positions of elements to swap.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] (To avoid conditional branches, the position is unconditionally stored at the end of the array, and the index of the end is incremented if a swap is needed.) A second pass exchanges the elements at the positions indicated in the arrays.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] Both loops have only one conditional branch, a test for termination, which is usually taken.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] The BlockQuicksort technique is incorporated into LLVM's C++ STL implementation, libcxx, providing a 50% improvement on random integer sequences.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] Pattern-defeating quicksort (pdqsort), a version of introsort, also incorporates this technique.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] Several variants of quicksort exist that separate the k smallest or largest elements from the rest of the input.
[src:quicksort-algorithm/quicksort-p02] Practical efficiency and smaller variance in performance were demonstrated against optimized quicksorts (of Sedgewick and Bentley-McIlroy).
